<br>
Anyway, I think that the willfulness displayed by people throughout history even to the point of self-destruction confirms this notion. If some fundamentalist wacko believes that he is inherently evil and paying for someone else's sin, I think he is already in hell. And if he is insisting that you believe as he does then he obviously has not learned the lesson contained in the Adam and Eve story.<br>
<br>
Can something in the Bible be true even if it never really happened? The story of the Prodigal Son is a great story. Is it any less so if Jesus was not talking about someone he actually knew? I don't think so. Therefore, the message of the Adam and Eve story does not rest on whether Adam and Eve actually existed, but on the message.<br>
<br>
By the way I am a PRACTICING Catholic. I would not presume to tell someone else how to live their faith, or lack of faith for that matter. I am not in that league. This is some of how I see this issue.<br>
<br>
MarleyMon<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :smokin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smokin.gif ALT=":smokin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
