First of all, humans, by being human, will share common tendencies.  We are pattern seeking, story telling creatures.  If we don’t know an answer we ask someone wiser.  If that wiser person spouts out a BS answer and we don’t test it ourselves, it can become treated as fact.  Just because a naturally superstitious creature spread across the planet naturally developed superstitions is no cause for it being true.  See the flat earth argument, the numbers fallacy or bandwagon one in other threads.  What you gloss over is that all over the planet, they developed <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>CONFLICTING</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> theologies.  This is not in support of your position, this undermines it.  Were there a revealed god, then they would all be the same faith.  You convincing Heather (Mom luvs em) that you are saved and she is wrong is more likely than you selling the fallacy of numbers here.  As stated previously, religion is a mechanism for controlling a population.  Tell the sheeple they are working on orders from god and they fall in line.  You find religions across the world for the same reason you find sexism across the world.  It is an effective means of control.  It is indoctrinated in the very young, it is punishable to question and ther leaders enjoy its support.  How else could we get such a moron as Dubya in office?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You also said there are no miracles that occur today and that God isnt talking to anyone? - Sorry, I have personally had miracles in my life and the life of my family. One such example was my dh met a woman in CA while on his mission. This woman had had a brain aneurysm and had the mental capabilty of a child. He and the other missionary that were with him gave her a blessing and she was Miraculously cured. Her brain function returned to normal. Faith alone isnt going to rebuild brain pathways - I know enough about medicine to know that brain cells just dont repair themselves instantaneously. Someone else (God) had a hand in it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Lovely anecdote, still totally lacking in evidentiary support.  Where is a medical report by separate physicians indicating the degree of her limitation?  What other elements were at play in the healing?  Was she being treated by anyone else?  Where is the report indicating how much of a recovery she made or how long it lasted?  What are the comparable rates of recidivism for her injury in the population at large?  Extraordinary claims require extensive evidence.  The child saying jeejee is wholly unremarkable given the extent of xian influence in a country like costa rica.  You were missionaries witnessing to them, how unlikely is it that this kid had seen a picture, since it hangs in just about every other home there?  Did none of his relatives ever visit?  No doubt they could just as easily have introduced him and begun his programming.  By not bothering to investigate these 'miracles' you are being irresponsible in your work for god.  You could be crediting the work improperly to him (Stealing, bearing false witness) or dropping the final proof of his existance and the worlds salvation into the toilet, costing him innumerable souls (please don't take this as an opportunity to explain why it may or may not apply to LDS, I don't care.  They are all myths, even yours. I am only interested in proof.)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>God currently 'speaks' to a prophet and his name is Gordon B Hinkley.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I highly doubt you’ll get many other faiths to support that claim.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As far as parenting and hoping to pass on beliefs go, I doubt it would thrill you to have one of your children &quot;find God.&quot; I think we are not so different <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I really wouldn’t care so long as they were healthy in its pursuit.  Pull out a wooden spoon on my grandkids and we have an issue.  Have a man tell my daughter her ‘place’ or lay a finger on her in anger and he has a real big issue.  I raise my kids to question everything and learn to evaluate what is true or not.  They can then draw their own conclusions.  This is a difference between teaching and indoctrinating.  Similar to the man and the fishes story.  Teach a kid how to think and they are prepared for life, teach them what to think and you’ve only programmed them.  I don’t want them to take anything just because someone said so.  Even from me.  If they don’t buy it, challenge me.  We can then go through all the steps of inquiry and reason and they can arrive at their own conclusions.<br>
<br>
Oddly enough, my daughter’s school is hosted by a church.  My wife is on the christian education board and I run their books.  We are acknowledged atheists and they don’t seem to have a problem with us.  They want me to join the choir.  My daughter occasionally goes to Sunday school because her friends do and she wants to join them.  She is armed with a critical eye and well-developed sense of logic.  She is also respectful enough not to tell people they are wrong, and the teachers know that if they challenge her she will respond in a way they may not want.  Mutual respect and tolerance.<br>
